SIMPLE: shelf
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shelf
<hw>Shelf</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Shelves</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>shelfe</ets>,
<ets>schelfe</ets>, AS. <ets>scylfe</ets>; akin to G.
<ets>schelfe</ets>, Icel. <ets>skj⟦amac⟧lf</ets>. In senses 2 & 3,
perhaps a different word (cf. <er>Shelve</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>).]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A flat tablet or ledge of any
material set horizontally at a distance from the floor, to hold objects
of use or ornament.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A sand bank in the sea, or a rock, or ledge of
rocks, rendering the water shallow, and dangerous to ships.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On the tawny sands and <qex>shelves</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On the secret <qex>shelves</qex> with fury cast.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A stratum lying in a very even
manner; a flat, projecting layer of rock.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A piece of timber running the
whole length of a vessel inside the timberheads.</def> <rj><au>D.
Kemp.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To lay on the shelf</b></col>, <cd>to lay aside as
unnecessary or useless; to dismiss; to discard.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shelfy</ent>⟦br⟧
